FooGallery.utils.Class.html.title: FooGallery.utils.Class
FooGallery.utils.Class.html.name: Class
FooGallery.utils.Class.html.summary: A base class providing some helper methods for prototypal inheritance.
FooGallery.utils.Class.html.description: This is a base class for making prototypal inheritance simpler to work with. It provides an easy way to inherit from another class and exposes a _super method within the scope of any overriding methods that allows a simple way to execute the overridden function. Have a look at the extend and override method examples to see some basic usage.

FooGallery.utils.Class.html#.extend.summary: Creates a new class that inherits from this one which in turn allows itself to be extended.
FooGallery.utils.Class.html#.extend.description: Every class created using this method has both the extend and override static methods added to it to allow it to be extended.

FooGallery.utils.Class.html#.override.description: This is a helper method for overriding a single function of a FooGallery.utils.Class or one of its child classes. This uses the FooGallery.utils.fn.addOrOverride method internally and simply provides the correct prototype.

FooGallery.utils.Factory.html.summary: A factory for classes allowing them to be registered and created using a friendly name.
FooGallery.utils.Factory.html.description: This class allows other classes to register themselves for use at a later time. Depending on how you intend to use the registered classes you can also specify a load and execution order through the priority parameter of the register method.

FooGallery.utils.Debugger.html.title: FooGallery.utils.Debugger
FooGallery.utils.Debugger.html.name: Debugger
FooGallery.utils.Debugger.html.summary: A debug utility class that can be enabled across sessions using the given key by storing its state in localStorage.
FooGallery.utils.Debugger.html.description: This class allows you to write additional debug info to the console within your code which by default is not actually output. You can then enable the debugger and it will start to output the results to the console. This most useful feature of this is the ability to store the debug state across page sessions by using localStorage. This allows you enable the debugger and then refresh the page to view any debugger output that occurs on page load.

FooGallery.utils.Debugger.html#key.title: key :string
FooGallery.utils.Debugger.html#key.name: key
FooGallery.utils.Debugger.html#key.summary: The key used to store the debug state in localStorage.

FooGallery.utils.Debugger.html#enabled.name: enabled
FooGallery.utils.Debugger.html#enabled.summary: Whether or not the debugger is currently enabled.
FooGallery.utils.Debugger.html#enabled.description: The value for this property is synced with the current state stored in localStorage and should never set from outside of this class.

FooGallery.utils.Debugger.html#enable.title: enable()
FooGallery.utils.Debugger.html#enable.name: enable
FooGallery.utils.Debugger.html#enable.summary: Enable the debugger causing additional info to be logged to the console.

FooGallery.utils.Debugger.html#log.name: log
FooGallery.utils.Debugger.html#log.summary: Logs the supplied message and additional arguments to the console when enabled.
FooGallery.utils.Debugger.html#log.description: This method basically wraps the console.log method and simply checks the enabled state of the debugger before passing along any supplied arguments.

FooGallery.utils.Debugger.html#logf.title: logf( message, replacements [, argN ] )
FooGallery.utils.Debugger.html#logf.name: logf
FooGallery.utils.Debugger.html#logf.summary: Logs the formatted message and additional arguments to the console when enabled.

FooGallery.utils.Debugger.html#disable.title: disable()
FooGallery.utils.Debugger.html#disable.name: disable
FooGallery.utils.Debugger.html#disable.summary: Disable the debugger stopping additional info being logged to the console.

FooGallery.utils.Throttle.html.title: FooGallery.utils.Throttle
FooGallery.utils.Throttle.html.name: Throttle
FooGallery.utils.Throttle.html.summary: A timer to throttle the execution of code.
FooGallery.utils.Throttle.html.description: This class is basically a wrapper around the window.setTimeout and window.clearTimeout functions. It was created to help throttle the execution of code in event handlers that could be called multiple times per second such as the window resize event. It is meant to limit the execution of expensive code until the specified idle time has lapsed. Take a look at the examples for the limit and clear methods for basic usage.

FooGallery.utils.Throttle.html#active.summary: Whether or not there is an active timer.

FooGallery.utils.Throttle.html#idle.name: idle
FooGallery.utils.Throttle.html#idle.summary: The idle time, in milliseconds, the timer should wait before executing the callback supplied to the limit method.

FooGallery.utils.Throttle.html#limit.title: limit( callback )
FooGallery.utils.Throttle.html#limit.name: limit
FooGallery.utils.Throttle.html#limit.summary: Starts a new timer clearing any previously set and executes the callback once it expires.

FooGallery.utils.Throttle.html#clear.title: clear()
FooGallery.utils.Throttle.html#clear.name: clear
FooGallery.utils.Throttle.html#clear.summary: Clear any previously set timer and prevent the execution of its' callback.

FooGallery.utils.Throttle.html#.extend.description: Every class created using this method has both the extend and override static methods added to it to allow it to be extended.

FooGallery.utils.fn.html#.CONTAINS_SUPER.name: CONTAINS_SUPER
FooGallery.utils.fn.html#.CONTAINS_SUPER.summary: The regular expression to test if a function uses the this._super method applied by the FooGallery.utils.fn.add method.
FooGallery.utils.fn.html#.CONTAINS_SUPER.description: When the script is first loaded into the page this performs a quick check to see if the browser supports function decompilation. If it does the regular expression is set to match the expected _super, however if function decompilation is not supported, the regular expression is set to match anything effectively making the test always return true.

FooGallery.utils.fn.html#.addOrOverride.title: <static> addOrOverride( proto, name, fn )
FooGallery.utils.fn.html#.addOrOverride.name: addOrOverride
FooGallery.utils.fn.html#.addOrOverride.summary: Adds or overrides the given method name on the proto using the supplied fn.
FooGallery.utils.fn.html#.addOrOverride.description: If the new method overrides a pre-existing one, this function will expose the overridden method as this._super within the new methods scope. This replaces having to write out the following to override a method and call its original: var original = MyClass.prototype.someMethod; MyClass.prototype.someMethod = function(arg1, arg2){ // execute the original original.call(this, arg1, arg2); };With the following: FooGallery.utils.fn.addOrOverride( MyClass.prototype, "someMethod", function(arg1, arg2){ // execute the original this._super(arg1, arg2); });This method is used by the FooGallery.utils.Class to implement the inheritance of individual methods.

FooGallery.utils.fn.html#.apply.title: <static> apply( klass [, args ] )  {function}
FooGallery.utils.fn.html#.apply.name: apply
FooGallery.utils.fn.html#.apply.summary: Use the Function.prototype.apply method on a class constructor using the new keyword.
FooGallery.utils.fn.html#.apply.description: When using the default Function.prototype.apply you can't use it on class constructors requiring the new keyword, this method allows us to do that.

FooGallery.utils.fn.html#.arg2arr.title: <static> arg2arr( args )  {Array}
FooGallery.utils.fn.html#.arg2arr.name: arg2arr
FooGallery.utils.fn.html#.arg2arr.summary: Converts the default arguments object into a proper array.
FooGallery.utils.fn.html#.arg2arr.description: This method is simply a replacement for calling Array.prototype.slice.call() to create an array from an arguments object.

FooGallery.utils.fn.html#.check.title: <static> check( thisArg, value [, def [, ctx ] ] )  {function}
FooGallery.utils.fn.html#.check.name: check
FooGallery.utils.fn.html#.check.summary: Checks the given value and ensures a function is returned.
FooGallery.utils.fn.html#.check.description: This function is primarily used to check the value of a callback option that could be supplied as either a function or a string. When just the function name is supplied this method uses the FooGallery.utils.fn.fetch method to resolve and wrap it to ensure when it's called the correct context is applied. Being able to resolve a function from a name allows callbacks to be easily set even through data attributes as you can just supply the full function name as a string and then use this method to retrieve the actual function.

FooGallery.utils.fn.html#.fetch.title: <static> fetch( name [, ctx ] )  {function}
FooGallery.utils.fn.html#.fetch.name: fetch
FooGallery.utils.fn.html#.fetch.summary: Fetches a function given its name.

FooGallery.utils.fn.html#.enqueue.title: <static> enqueue( objects, name [, arg1 [, ...argN ] ] )  {jQuery.Promise}
FooGallery.utils.fn.html#.enqueue.name: enqueue
FooGallery.utils.fn.html#.enqueue.summary: Enqueues methods using the given name from all supplied objects and executes each in order with the given arguments.
FooGallery.utils.fn.html#.enqueue.description: This method allows an array of objects that implement a common set of methods to be executed in a supplied order. Each method in the queue is only executed after the successful completion of the previous. Success is evaluated as the method did not throw an error and if it returned a promise it was resolved. An example of this being used within the plugin is the loading and execution of methods on the various components. Using this method ensures components are loaded and have their methods executed in a static order regardless of when they were registered with the plugin or if the method is async. This way if ComponentB's preinit relies on properties set in ComponentA's preinit method you can register ComponentB with a lower priority than ComponentA and you can be assured ComponentA's preinit completed successfully before ComponentB's preinit is called event if it performs an async operation.

FooGallery.utils.url.html#.full.name: full
FooGallery.utils.url.html#.full.summary: Given a url that could be relative or full this ensures a full url is returned.

FooGallery.utils.str.html#.from.name: from
FooGallery.utils.str.html#.from.summary: Returns the remainder of the target split on the first index of the given substr.

FooGallery.utils.str.html#.join.summary: Joins any number of strings using the given separator.
FooGallery.utils.str.html#.join.description: This method differs from using the standard Array.prototype.join function to join strings in that it ignores empty parts and checks to see if each starts with the supplied separator. If the part starts with the separator it is removed before appending it to the final result.

FooGallery.utils.str.html#.format.summary: A basic string formatter that can use both index and name based placeholders but handles only string or number replacements.
FooGallery.utils.str.html#.format.description: This method allows you to supply the replacements as an object when using named placeholders or as an array or additional arguments when using index placeholders. This does not perform a simultaneous replacement of placeholders, which is why it's referred to as a basic formatter. This means replacements that contain placeholders within there value could end up being replaced themselves as seen in the last example.

If you want to map a property from/to a child object on either the source or target objects you must supply the name using . notation as seen in the below example with the "name.first" to "Name.Short" mapping.

FooGallery.utils.obj.html#~Validators.description: The validators object is a single level object. If you want to validate a property of a child object you must supply the name using . notation as seen in the below example with the "name.first" and "name.last" properties. Any function that accepts a value to test as the first argument and returns a boolean can be used as a validator. This means the majority of the FooGallery.utils.is methods can be used directly. If the property supports multiple types just provide your own function as seen with "name.last" in the below example.

FooGallery.utils.transition.html#.suppor.name: supported

FooGallery.utils.transition.html#.end.description: Depending on the browser this returns one of the following values: "transitionend""webkitTransitionEnd""msTransitionEnd""oTransitionEnd"null - If the browser doesn't support transitions

FooGallery.utils.transition.html#.durati.title: <static> duration( $element [, def ] )  {number}
FooGallery.utils.transition.html#.durati.name: duration
FooGallery.utils.transition.html#.durati.summary: Gets the transition-duration value for the supplied jQuery element.

FooGallery.utils.transition.html#.start.title: <static> start( $element, className [, state [, timeout ] ] )  {jQuery.Deferred}
FooGallery.utils.transition.html#.start.name: start
FooGallery.utils.transition.html#.start.summary: Start a transition by toggling the supplied className on the $element.
FooGallery.utils.transition.html#.start.description: This method lets us use CSS transitions by toggling a class and using the transitionend event to perform additional actions once the transition has completed across all browsers. In browsers that do not support transitions this method would behave the same as if just calling jQuery's .toggleClass method. The last parameter timeout is used to create a timer that behaves as a safety net in case the transitionend event is never raised and ensures the deferred returned by this method is resolved or rejected within a specified time.

FooGallery.html.title: FooGallery
FooGallery.html.name: FooGallery
FooGallery.html.summary: The core namespace for the plugin containing all its code.
FooGallery.html.description: This plugin houses all it's code within a single FooGallery global variable to prevent polluting the global namespace and to make accessing its various members simpler.

FooGallery.html#.$.title: <static> $ :jQuery
FooGallery.html#.$.summary: A reference to the jQuery object the plugin is registered with.
FooGallery.html#.$.description: This is used internally for all jQuery operations to help work around issues where multiple jQuery libraries have been included in a single page.

FooGallery.html#.ready.title: <static> ready( callback )
FooGallery.html#.ready.name: ready
FooGallery.html#.ready.summary: Waits for the DOM to be accessible and then executes the supplied callback.

FooGallery.html#.getImages.title: <static> getImages( target )  {jQuery}
FooGallery.html#.getImages.name: getImages
FooGallery.html#.getImages.summary: Gets all images from the supplied target that have a width and height attribute set.

FooGallery.html#.addSize.title: <static> addSize( target [, checkContainer ] )
FooGallery.html#.addSize.name: addSize
FooGallery.html#.addSize.summary: Sets an inline CSS width and height value for the provided target images calculated from there width and height attributes.
FooGallery.html#.addSize.description: This method is used on page load to calculate a CSS width and height for images that have yet to be loaded. This is done to avoid layout jumps and is needed as for responsive images to work in most layouts they must have a CSS width of 100% and a height of auto. This allows the browser to automatically calculate the height to display the image without causing any stretching.The problem with this approach is that it leads to layout jumps as before the image is loaded and the browser can determine its size it is simply displayed in the page as a 0 height block at 100% width of its' container. This method fixes this issue by setting a CSS width and height for all images supplied.

FooGallery.html#.removeSize.title: <static> removeSize( target )
FooGallery.html#.removeSize.name: removeSize
FooGallery.html#.removeSize.summary: Removes any inline CSS width and height value for the provided target images.

FooGallery.html#~readyCallback.name: readyCallback
